research/history/logs/agent_action_0020.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"Round 19 showed that `topk/signum/LR=1.6e-3/EF=12` at `K=8` suffered a large quality drop and much heavier dead-feature pressure, with the late curve nearly flattening but not fully collapsing. This round changes only `K`, moving from `8` to `4`, to answer the single remaining boundary question: whether the current export-compatible topk recipe has any usable signal left at the absolute minimum allowed K, or whether `K=8` already marks the effective floor.","summary":"Finish the current low-K boundary sweep on the active topk mainline: keep `ARCHITECTURE=topk`, `OPTIMIZER=signum`, `LR=1.6e-3`, and `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12` fixed, and reduce `K` from `8` to `4` to locate the hard lower bound of the present topk/signum regime.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"full","expected_win":"smaller_k","family_name":"topk","family_stage":"mainline","self_review":"This stays on the active `topk` family, changes exactly one primary variable (`k`), respects the fixed `EF=12` rule and allowed-K set, and closes the current K-only frontier scan cleanly. The main risk is that `K=4` may be clearly past the useful regime, but `command=\"stop\"` is disallowed and this is the most informative remaining single-variable question because it determines whether `K=8` is merely weak or already beyond the practical floor.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"topk"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"1.6e-3"},{"key":"K","value":"4"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"12"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["Round 19 (`K=8`) reached `FVU=0.380331814289093`, a large degradation from `K=16`, while late-phase improvement became very small.","At `K=8`, late `dead_pct` rose to about `0.39` and `auxk` stayed high at about `0.37`, indicating strong capacity stress and likely growing online compensation burden.","Even though the late curve nearly flattened at `K=8`, it did not fully collapse, so running `K=4` is the cleanest way to locate the hard lower boundary of the current topk/signum/EF12 recipe."],"next_hypotheses":["If `K=4` collapses or adds very little usable signal, treat `K=8` or `K=16` as the practical floor and return to non-K recipe tuning on the same family.","If `K=4` is surprisingly stable, compare it against `K=8` strictly as a deployment tradeoff point rather than against the K128 anchor.","After the hard lower bound is mapped, the next mainline question should move back to recipe tuning within the surviving low-K regime rather than continuing K-only descent."],"primary_variable":"k"}
research/history/logs/agent_action_0024.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"Round 23 showed that increasing `AUXK_ALPHA` above the `topk/signum/K128/EF12/LR=1.6e-3` reference did not improve the anchor recipe, which suggests the mainline is likely saturated on auxiliary-loss magnitude itself. This round changes only `DEAD_FEATURE_THRESHOLD`, lowering it from the effectively inactive `10000000` to `100000`, to test whether earlier dead-feature rescue improves late-stage reconstruction or curve shape without changing the core topk recipe.","summary":"Run a single loss-schedule test on the exact topk mainline reference recipe: keep `ARCHITECTURE=topk`, `OPTIMIZER=signum`, `LR=1.6e-3`, `K=128`, `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12`, and `AUXK_ALPHA=0.03125` fixed, and reduce `DEAD_FEATURE_THRESHOLD` to `100000` to see whether activating auxiliary rescue earlier helps the K128 baseline.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"full","expected_win":"lower_fvu","family_name":"topk","family_stage":"mainline","self_review":"This stays on the active `topk` family, changes only one non-core variable on the exact reference backbone, respects the fixed `EF=12` rule, and follows directly from the evidence that both weaker and stronger `AUXK_ALPHA` failed to beat the baseline. The main risk is that the threshold change may have little effect over this training horizon, but it is the cleanest remaining single-variable way to probe whether the auxiliary mechanism is mis-timed rather than mis-scaled.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"topk"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"1.6e-3"},{"key":"K","value":"128"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"12"},{"key":"AUXK_ALPHA","value":"0.03125"},{"key":"DEAD_FEATURE_THRESHOLD","value":"100000"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["Round 14 (`AUXK_ALPHA=0.015625`) and Round 23 (`AUXK_ALPHA=0.0625`) both failed to improve the K128 anchor, so the mainline loss axis now looks saturated on magnitude.","The next clean question is whether the auxiliary dead-feature mechanism is mistimed rather than misweighted; the current threshold `10000000` is effectively inactive over this run length.","Judge this run by full curve shape as well as final FVU: if earlier rescue smooths late descent or lowers FVU, the issue was activation timing; if not, the current topk/signum/K128 recipe is likely saturated on the aux-loss path."],"next_hypotheses":["If lowering `DEAD_FEATURE_THRESHOLD` improves the K128 reference, continue refining that schedule on the same backbone before moving to other recipe axes.","If earlier dead-feature rescue does not help, treat the current loss path as saturated and move to a different single recipe variable.","If lowering the threshold hurts stability or reconstruction, keep the effectively inactive dead-feature schedule as the better mainline choice."],"primary_variable":"other_param"}
research/history/round_summaries/round_0205.json:7:  "family_name": "factorized_topk",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0205.json:19:    "hypothesis": "\u5019\u9009 family: factorized_topk\u3002\u6700\u7ec8\u91cd\u6784\u516c\u5f0f\u4e3a x_hat = \u03a3_i alpha_i b_i\uff0c\u5176\u4e2d b_i \u6765\u81ea\u5355\u4e2a\u9759\u6001\u5411\u91cf\u5e93\uff1bfactorized scorer \u4ec5\u7528\u4e8e\u5728\u7ebf\u6253\u5206\u4e0e\u9009\u5740\uff0c\u5bfc\u51fa\u5230 LUTurbo/Lottable \u65f6\u4ecd\u662f\u5355\u5e93\u67e5\u8868\u52a0\u6743\u6c42\u548c\uff0c\u56e0\u6b64\u5c5e\u4e8e\u76f4\u63a5\u517c\u5bb9\u3002\u57fa\u4e8e r204 \u5df2\u5728 K=64\u3001EF=2 \u4e0b\u62ff\u5230 0.44x / 0.3013 \u7684 <0.5x \u70b9\uff0c\u672c\u8f6e\u7ee7\u7eed\u4fdd\u6301 architecture\u3001EF\u3001optimizer\u3001LR \u4e0d\u53d8\uff0c\u4ec5\u5c06 K \u4ece 64 \u4e0b\u63a2\u5230 32\uff0c\u9884\u8ba1 deployment cost \u53ef\u7531\u7ea6 0.06x \u8fdb\u4e00\u6b65\u964d\u5230\u7ea6 0.03x\uff0c\u4f7f total_cost \u7ea6\u843d\u5728 0.41x\uff0c\u8865\u5168\u66f4\u4f4e\u6210\u672c\u7aef\u8986\u76d6\uff0c\u5e76\u68c0\u9a8c\u8be5 family \u5728\u66f4\u77ed\u67e5\u8868\u94fe\u8def\u4e0b\u7684 FVU \u9000\u5316\u659c\u7387\u3002",
