research/history/logs/agent_action_0064.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"With the `gated` mainline stalled for eleven rounds and the lighter selector probes `group_topk` and `bucketed_topk` both coming back clearly worse, the next highest-value matched architecture probe is `codebook_topk`: it remains LUTurbo-compatible because the reconstruction is still a finite sum over static libraries, but it changes the architecture by adding a hard coarse codebook selection before the sparse residual. This round answers one question only: under the matched `K=128`, `signum`, `LR=2.0e-3`, `EF=12` recipe, is `codebook_topk` intrinsically strong enough to justify any later follow-up, or should it be ruled out immediately.","summary":"Run one matched architecture probe by switching `ARCHITECTURE` from `gated` to `codebook_topk` while keeping `K=128`, `OPTIMIZER=signum`, `LR=2.0e-3`, and `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12` fixed.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"full","expected_win":"explore_unknown","family_name":"codebook_topk","family_stage":"prototype","self_review":"This obeys the Round 64 policy by changing exactly one primary variable: architecture. `codebook_topk` is a better remaining probe than batch-coupled variants because it stays single-sample deployable, and it is more informative than heavier multi-branch gating because it tests a distinct static-library decomposition pattern that could plausibly trade some sparse support work for a coarse lookup plus residual correction.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"codebook_topk"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"2.0e-3"},{"key":"K","value":"128"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"12"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["Round 64 spends the single allowed matched architecture probe on `codebook_topk` after `group_topk` and `bucketed_topk` both failed to beat the matched `gated` control.","`codebook_topk` is extended-compatible with LUTurbo because the final reconstruction can be exported as a hard-selected static coarse codebook vector plus a finite weighted sum over a static residual decoder library.","Judge this probe strictly as a family-worthiness test against matched `gated` K128: if it is clearly worse, discard it and return to the `gated` mainline next round; if it is competitive, record the result but still return to the mainline per policy."],"next_hypotheses":["If `codebook_topk` is clearly worse than matched `gated`, discard the family and return to the `gated` mainline next round.","If `codebook_topk` is roughly competitive, record it as a possible coarse-plus-residual deployment direction but still return to the `gated` mainline next round per policy.","If `codebook_topk` unexpectedly beats matched `gated`, schedule at most one later follow-up after the mandated return to the `gated` mainline."],"primary_variable":"architecture"}
research/history/logs/agent_action_0086.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"After `routed_lowrank_two_stage_residual` and `lowrank_residual_vq` both failed to pressure the `lowrank_two_stage_residual` K128 anchor, the most informative single matched architecture probe is `lowrank_jumprelu_residual`. It preserves the same low-rank static-library export path while collapsing the selector back to a single residual pass with thresholded support selection, which is more promising for LUTurbo's total online cost (`selection + coeffs + lookup + compensation`) than another multi-stage or routed variant. If it is still clearly weaker under the exact matched `K=128, OPTIMIZER=signum, LR=2.0e-3, EXPANSION_FACTOR=12` recipe, then this simpler low-rank single-stage family is not worth continuing in the current regime.","summary":"Run one matched architecture probe by switching `ARCHITECTURE` to `lowrank_jumprelu_residual` while keeping `K=128`, `OPTIMIZER=signum`, `LR=2.0e-3`, and `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12` fixed.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"full","expected_win":"lower_cost","family_name":"lowrank_jumprelu_residual","family_stage":"prototype","self_review":"This obeys the round rule by changing exactly one primary variable: `architecture`. I kept the current mainline recipe fixed, explicitly pinned `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12`, and chose a candidate that is LUTurbo-compatible and meaningfully simpler online than the current two-stage mainline. Risk: older low-K evidence for this family was weak, so this may just confirm that the simpler single-stage thresholded selector cannot retain enough quality at matched K128.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"lowrank_jumprelu_residual"},{"key":"K","value":"128"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"2.0e-3"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"12"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["Round 86 spends the single allowed matched architecture probe on `lowrank_jumprelu_residual` against the exact `lowrank_two_stage_residual` K128/EF12/signum/LR=2.0e-3 anchor.","Judge this run as a family-worthiness test for a simpler low-rank single-stage thresholded selector that may reduce LUTurbo online selection and compensation cost; return to the `lowrank_two_stage_residual` mainline next round regardless of outcome."],"next_hypotheses":["If `lowrank_jumprelu_residual` is clearly weaker than the matched `lowrank_two_stage_residual` anchor, discard it and resume mainline tuning on `lowrank_two_stage_residual` next round.","If `lowrank_jumprelu_residual` is unexpectedly competitive at matched K128, record it as a viable lower-online-complexity branch but still return to the mainline next round per probe policy."],"primary_variable":"architecture"}
research/history/round_summaries/round_0037.json:19:    "hypothesis": "Because `gated` beat the matched `topk` control at `K=96`, the next single question is whether that advantage extends one more step down the support ladder; testing `ARCHITECTURE=gated, K=64, EF=12, OPTIMIZER=signum, LR=1.6e-3` will show whether `gated` is broadly stronger across high-K frontier points or only wins near the very top end.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0037.json:20:    "summary": "Round 36 changed the picture: `gated@96` is not just viable, it improved the frontier over the existing `topk@96` control, so the family has earned one more K-mapping round. Keep the anchored recipe fixed and step only `K` from `96` to `64`. This directly answers whether the `gated` advantage generalizes to the next adjacent frontier point. Read the full curve, not just the endpoint: if training remains smooth and finishes below the `topk@64` control (`0.1992608`), `gated` is a real high-K mainline candidate; if it drops back behind `topk`, then the family likely helps only in the upper-K regime.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0037.json:51:      "Round 36 established that gated generalizes beyond K=128 by beating the matched topk control at K=96.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0037.json:55:      "If `gated@64` also beats `topk@64`, continue one more downward K probe because gated is shaping up as the stronger mainline family across multiple frontier points.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0037.json:56:      "If `gated@64` falls back behind `topk@64`, treat gated as a high-K specialist and preserve it mainly for K>=96."
