research/history/round_summaries/round_0022.json:7:  "family_name": "topk",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0022.json:17:    "hypothesis": "Round 21 showed that `topk/signum/LR=1.6e-3/EF=12` at `K=96` is a promising high-quality reduced-cost point: its curve kept descending smoothly through the late phase, and both `dead_pct` and `auxk` stayed very low. This round changes only the loss-shaping axis, lowering `AUXK_ALPHA` from `0.03125` to `0.015625` while keeping the `K=96` recipe fixed, to answer whether the new near-anchor deployment point is slightly over-regularized and can recover a bit more reconstruction quality without destabilizing training.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0022.json:18:    "summary": "Run a single loss-axis test on the newly validated `K=96` topk point: keep `ARCHITECTURE=topk`, `OPTIMIZER=signum`, `LR=1.6e-3`, `K=96`, and `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12` fixed, and reduce `AUXK_ALPHA` to `0.015625` to see whether weaker auxiliary pressure improves the high-quality reduced-cost recipe.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0022.json:21:    "family_name": "topk",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0022.json:23:    "self_review": "This stays on the active `topk` family, changes exactly one primary variable (`other_param` via `AUXK_ALPHA`), respects the fixed `EF=12` rule, and follows directly from the observed `K=96` curve shape. The main risk is that the gain may be small, but `K=96` is now the most promising reduced-cost point and its very low dead-feature pressure makes a clean over-regularization check more justified than continuing to remap K.",
