research/history/round_summaries/round_0208.json:77:    "self_review": "\u8be5\u63d0\u6848\u4e25\u683c\u9075\u5b88\u5355\u53d8\u91cf\u539f\u5219\uff0c\u5e76\u76f4\u63a5\u670d\u52a1\u4e8e\u5f53\u524d <0.5x \u533a\u57df\u8865\u70b9\u76ee\u6807\u3002\u4e3b\u8981\u98ce\u9669\u662f EF=1 \u53ef\u80fd\u4f7f topk \u8868\u8fbe\u80fd\u529b\u4e0b\u964d\u8f83\u591a\uff0c\u4f46\u5176\u4fe1\u606f\u4ef7\u503c\u9ad8\uff0c\u56e0\u4e3a\u5b83\u80fd\u76f4\u63a5\u56de\u7b54\u975e factorized \u7b80\u5355\u67b6\u6784\u80fd\u5426\u5728\u771f\u6b63\u4f4e\u6210\u672c\u533a\u7ad9\u4f4f\u811a\u3002",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0036.json:20:    "summary": "Round 35 answered the preprocess probe: Hadamard did not improve the anchored `gated` recipe, leaving no meaningful recipe knobs unexplored in the prescribed order. The next single-variable move is therefore `K`. Use the plain `gated` anchor and drop only `K` to `96`. This is the highest-value neighboring check because there is already a strong `topk` control at `K=96` (`0.171856`), so the run directly tells us whether `gated` has broader family viability or whether it should be treated as a narrow `K=128` specialization. Read the curve shape as well as the endpoint: if `gated@96` is smooth and beats or matches the `topk@96` control comfortably, keep the family alive across K; if it is clearly worse or unstable, treat `gated` as exhausted outside the single `K=128` point.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0036.json:25:    "self_review": "This keeps the same family, preserves EF at 12, changes exactly one primary variable (`K`), and only moves K after the LR, optimizer, loss, and preprocess probes failed to improve the anchored recipe. Choosing `K=96` minimizes extrapolation because it is adjacent to the current gated anchor and has a matched topk frontier point for direct comparison.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0036.json:52:      "Compare gated@96 against the existing topk@96 control and judge curve shape, not just terminal FVU; this determines whether gated generalizes beyond the isolated K=128 win."
research/history/round_summaries/round_0036.json:55:      "If `gated@96` is competitive with or better than `topk@96`, gated deserves at least one more K-mapping round within the allowed grid.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0036.json:56:      "If `gated@96` clearly trails `topk@96`, stop spending mainline rounds on gated except as the recorded K=128 incumbent."
research/history/round_summaries/round_0036.json:76:    "description": "Round 35 answered the preprocess probe: Hadamard did not improve the anchored `gated` recipe, leaving no meaningful recipe knobs unexplored in the prescribed order. The next single-variable move is therefore `K`. Use the plain `gated` anchor and drop only `K` to `96`. This is the highest-value neighboring check because there is already a strong `topk` control at `K=96` (`0.171856`), so the run directly tells us whether `gated` has broader family viability or whether it should be treated as a narrow `K=128` specialization. Read the curve shape as well as the endpoint: if `gated@96` is smooth and beats or matches the `topk@96` control comfortably, keep the family alive across K; if it is clearly worse or unstable, treat `gated` as exhausted outside the single `K=128` point.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0036.json:77:    "self_review": "This keeps the same family, preserves EF at 12, changes exactly one primary variable (`K`), and only moves K after the LR, optimizer, loss, and preprocess probes failed to improve the anchored recipe. Choosing `K=96` minimizes extrapolation because it is adjacent to the current gated anchor and has a matched topk frontier point for direct comparison.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0021.json:7:  "family_name": "topk",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0021.json:19:    "hypothesis": "Round 20 showed that `topk/signum/LR=1.6e-3/EF=12` at `K=4` is effectively past the practical floor: the late-phase FVU curve flattened completely while dead-feature pressure rose to about `0.68`, so further low-K descent is no longer the right question. This round changes only `K`, moving from the quality anchor side to `K=96`, to test whether LUTurbo can obtain a materially cheaper but still high-quality deployment point that may be more practical than the stressed ultra-low-K regime.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0021.json:20:    "summary": "Shift the K sweep from the collapsed extreme low end to the unexplored moderate-cost region: keep `ARCHITECTURE=topk`, `OPTIMIZER=signum`, `LR=1.6e-3`, and `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12` fixed, and set `K=96` to measure whether a near-anchor quality point exists between the current `K=64` and `K=128` frontier points.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0021.json:23:    "family_name": "topk",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0021.json:25:    "self_review": "This stays on the active `topk` mainline, changes exactly one primary variable (`k`), respects the fixed `EF=12` rule and allowed-K set, and asks a single clean frontier question. The main risk is that `K=96` may add little beyond interpolation, but after `K=4` and `K=8` showed strong capacity stress, probing the moderate-K gap is a more deployment-relevant use of the same single-axis budget than continuing to push or retread the collapsed low end.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0021.json:30:        "value": "topk"
research/history/round_summaries/round_0021.json:51:      "Round 20 (`K=4`) appears to mark the hard lower bound of the current topk/signum regime: late improvement vanished while `dead_pct` climbed to about `0.68` and `auxk` remained around `0.58`.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0021.json:58:      "If `K=96` underperforms unexpectedly, re-check whether the current topk recipe is over-specialized to either very high or very low K and then move back to one recipe axis."
research/history/round_summaries/round_0021.json:69:    "architecture": "topk",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0021.json:78:    "description": "Shift the K sweep from the collapsed extreme low end to the unexplored moderate-cost region: keep `ARCHITECTURE=topk`, `OPTIMIZER=signum`, `LR=1.6e-3`, and `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12` fixed, and set `K=96` to measure whether a near-anchor quality point exists between the current `K=64` and `K=128` frontier points.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0021.json:79:    "self_review": "This stays on the active `topk` mainline, changes exactly one primary variable (`k`), respects the fixed `EF=12` rule and allowed-K set, and asks a single clean frontier question. The main risk is that `K=96` may add little beyond interpolation, but after `K=4` and `K=8` showed strong capacity stress, probing the moderate-K gap is a more deployment-relevant use of the same single-axis budget than continuing to push or retread the collapsed low end.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0024.json:7:  "family_name": "topk",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0024.json:19:    "hypothesis": "Round 23 showed that increasing `AUXK_ALPHA` above the `topk/signum/K128/EF12/LR=1.6e-3` reference did not improve the anchor recipe, which suggests the mainline is likely saturated on auxiliary-loss magnitude itself. This round changes only `DEAD_FEATURE_THRESHOLD`, lowering it from the effectively inactive `10000000` to `100000`, to test whether earlier dead-feature rescue improves late-stage reconstruction or curve shape without changing the core topk recipe.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0024.json:20:    "summary": "Run a single loss-schedule test on the exact topk mainline reference recipe: keep `ARCHITECTURE=topk`, `OPTIMIZER=signum`, `LR=1.6e-3`, `K=128`, `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12`, and `AUXK_ALPHA=0.03125` fixed, and reduce `DEAD_FEATURE_THRESHOLD` to `100000` to see whether activating auxiliary rescue earlier helps the K128 baseline.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0024.json:23:    "family_name": "topk",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0024.json:25:    "self_review": "This stays on the active `topk` family, changes only one non-core variable on the exact reference backbone, respects the fixed `EF=12` rule, and follows directly from the evidence that both weaker and stronger `AUXK_ALPHA` failed to beat the baseline. The main risk is that the threshold change may have little effect over this training horizon, but it is the cleanest remaining single-variable way to probe whether the auxiliary mechanism is mis-timed rather than mis-scaled.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0024.json:30:        "value": "topk"
research/history/round_summaries/round_0024.json:61:      "Judge this run by full curve shape as well as final FVU: if earlier rescue smooths late descent or lowers FVU, the issue was activation timing; if not, the current topk/signum/K128 recipe is likely saturated on the aux-loss path."
