research/history/round_summaries/round_0024.json:86:    "description": "Run a single loss-schedule test on the exact topk mainline reference recipe: keep `ARCHITECTURE=topk`, `OPTIMIZER=signum`, `LR=1.6e-3`, `K=128`, `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12`, and `AUXK_ALPHA=0.03125` fixed, and reduce `DEAD_FEATURE_THRESHOLD` to `100000` to see whether activating auxiliary rescue earlier helps the K128 baseline.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0024.json:87:    "self_review": "This stays on the active `topk` family, changes only one non-core variable on the exact reference backbone, respects the fixed `EF=12` rule, and follows directly from the evidence that both weaker and stronger `AUXK_ALPHA` failed to beat the baseline. The main risk is that the threshold change may have little effect over this training horizon, but it is the cleanest remaining single-variable way to probe whether the auxiliary mechanism is mis-timed rather than mis-scaled.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0212.json:17:    "hypothesis": "\u5019\u9009 family: lowrank_factorized_residual\u3002\u6700\u7ec8\u91cd\u6784\u516c\u5f0f\u4e3a x_hat = \u03a3_r beta_r u_r + \u03a3_i alpha_i b_i\uff0c\u5176\u4e2d {u_r} \u662f\u9759\u6001 trunk \u5411\u91cf\u5e93\u3001{b_i} \u662f\u9759\u6001 residual \u5411\u91cf\u5e93\uff1bfactorized scorer \u53ea\u5f71\u54cd\u5728\u7ebf\u9009\u62e9\u4e0e\u7cfb\u6570\u8ba1\u7b97\uff0c\u4e0d\u6539\u53d8 decoder \u7aef\u7684\u9759\u6001\u5e93\u6709\u9650\u52a0\u6743\u548c\u5f62\u5f0f\uff0c\u56e0\u6b64\u53ef\u5bfc\u51fa\u5230 LUTurbo/Lottable \u7684\u201c\u67e5\u8868 + \u52a0\u6743\u6c42\u548c + \u9009\u62e9\u6027\u8865\u507f\u201d\u94fe\u8def\uff0c\u517c\u5bb9\u6027\u4e3a\u6269\u5c55\u517c\u5bb9\u3002\u5355\u4e3b\u53d8\u91cf\u9009\u62e9 TRUNK_RANK\uff1a\u5728\u4fdd\u6301 ARCHITECTURE=lowrank_factorized_residual\u3001K=64\u3001EF=1\u3001signum\u3001LR=3e-3 \u4e0d\u53d8\u65f6\uff0c\u628a trunk_rank \u4ece\u5f53\u524d auto\u2248128 \u4e0b\u8c03\u5230 32\uff0c\u6d4b\u8bd5\u5f53\u524d 0.69x \u70b9\u7684\u4e3b\u8981\u5197\u4f59\u662f\u5426\u6765\u81ea\u8fc7\u5927\u7684 trunk \u5e93\uff1b\u82e5 trunk \u53ea\u662f\u63d0\u4f9b\u7c97\u8865\u507f\u800c residual \u5206\u652f\u5df2\u627f\u62c5\u4e3b\u8981\u8868\u8fbe\uff0c\u5219\u53ef\u628a encoder+deployment \u603b\u6210\u672c\u4e00\u53e3\u6c14\u538b\u5165 <0.5x \u533a\u57df\uff0c\u540c\u65f6\u7ef4\u6301\u660e\u663e\u4f18\u4e8e topk@0.31x \u7684 FVU\u3002",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0212.json:54:      "r210 \u5728 0.69x \u5904\u53d6\u5f97 0.1256 FVU\uff0c\u4e14 tokens_per_sec\u2248166.6k\u3001\u603b\u8017\u65f6 291s\uff0c\u660e\u663e\u5feb\u4e8e\u8fd1\u671f topk/soft-codebook \u7ebf\uff1b\u56e0\u6b64\u4f18\u5148\u538b\u7f29 trunk_rank \u6bd4\u7ee7\u7eed\u589e\u5927 K \u66f4\u7b26\u5408\u5f53\u524d\u4f4e\u5f00\u9500\u4e0e\u8bad\u7ec3\u6210\u672c\u53cc\u76ee\u6807\u3002"
research/history/round_summaries/round_0212.json:57:      "\u5982\u679c TRUNK_RANK=32 \u4ecd\u4fdd\u6301\u660e\u663e\u4f18\u4e8e topk@EF1,K64 \u7684 FVU \u4e14\u8fdb\u5165 <0.5x\uff0c\u5219\u56fa\u5b9a\u8be5 family \u540e\u53ea\u6cbf K \u8f74\u505a\u4e00\u6b21\u8865\u70b9\u3002",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0212.json:58:      "\u5982\u679c TRUNK_RANK=32 \u7684 FVU \u9000\u5316\u8fc7\u5927\uff0c\u5219\u8bf4\u660e\u8be5 family \u7684\u6536\u76ca\u9ad8\u5ea6\u4f9d\u8d56 trunk \u5bb9\u91cf\uff0c\u4f4e\u5f00\u9500\u4e3b\u6218\u573a\u5e94\u56de\u5230\u66f4\u77ed\u94fe\u8def\u7684 topk \u6216\u65b0\u7684\u8f7b\u91cf\u5355\u5e93\u65b9\u6848\u3002"
research/history/logs/agent_action_0009.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"Round 8 showed that swapping `topk` from `signum` to `adam` while keeping `LR=1.6e-3` caused a large quality collapse, which is more consistent with Adam being mis-tuned than with the optimizer family being unusable. This round changes only Adam's learning rate, backing off to `8e-4` while keeping `topk/K=128/EF=12` fixed, to test whether Adam can recover a stable training curve and competitive FVU at a smaller step size.","summary":"Run one Adam LR callback: keep `ARCHITECTURE=topk`, `K=128`, and `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12` fixed, and reduce Adam LR from `1.6e-3` to `8e-4` to determine whether round 8 was primarily an overshoot issue.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"full","expected_win":"lower_fvu","family_name":"topk","family_stage":"mainline","self_review":"This stays on the active `topk` family, respects the round-9 priority order, and changes only one primary variable (`lr`). I avoided opening a new family or changing `K` before completing the requested optimizer retune step.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"topk"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"adam"},{"key":"LR","value":"8e-4"},{"key":"K","value":"128"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"12"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["Round 8's `adam@1.6e-3` collapse should be treated first as an Adam LR mismatch, not as a definitive optimizer verdict.","This round performs the required one-step Adam LR callback while holding `topk/K128/EF12` constant for clean attribution.","Judge the run by full training-curve shape as well as terminal FVU: recovery from early instability or smoother late descent would keep Adam viable even if it does not immediately beat signum."],"next_hypotheses":["If `adam@8e-4` is still unstable or much worse than signum, Adam likely needs an even smaller LR or can be deprioritized.","If `adam@8e-4` is stable and materially better, stay in `topk` and continue Adam-only LR tuning.","If `adam@8e-4` is merely stable but not competitive, compare curve shape against signum before deciding whether to terminate the Adam branch."],"primary_variable":"lr"}
research/history/logs/agent_action_0201.json:1:{"change_type":"architecture","command":"run","env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"lowrank_soft_codebook_residual"}],"expected_win":"clarify_frontier","experiment_tier":"full","family_name":"lowrank_soft_codebook_residual","family_stage":"active_baseline_probe","hypothesis":"Matched architecture probe under the fixed mainline recipe. Final reconstruction formula is x_hat = U(Vx) + Σ_m pi_m c_m + Σ_i alpha_i b_i. This is LUTurbo 扩展兼容 because the low-rank trunk term U(Vx) can be exported as a static trunk vector library, the soft codebook term Σ_m pi_m c_m uses a static codebook library, and the sparse residual term Σ_i alpha_i b_i uses a static residual dictionary, so LUTurbo/Lottable inference remains static lookup plus weighted summation plus optional residual compensation. Holding K=128, EXPANSION_FACTOR=2, OPTIMIZER=signum, and LR=3.0e-3 fixed, this probe isolates whether the second residual refinement stage in lowrank_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual is actually buying enough FVU to justify its extra encoder selection cost and runtime overhead in the feasible low-EF regime.","needs_sanity":false,"next_hypotheses":["Return to the lowrank_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual mainline next round as required by policy.","If lowrank_soft_codebook_residual is close in FVU while materially faster or cheaper at the same K/EF recipe, treat the second residual stage as weak value in the current LUTurbo-compatible regime."],"notes_to_memory":["Compatibility label: 扩展兼容.","This is a parent-family matched probe, not a new incompatible line: same trunk+codebook decomposition, only removes the second sparse refinement branch.","Selection-cost rationale: this family is comfortably feasible at EF=2 and materially cheaper than the two-stage parent, making it the cleanest architecture-only test of whether stage-2 refinement is worth keeping.","Judge the result using both FVU and runtime counters (tokens_per_sec, total wall time, final_total_tokens), because recent rounds show meaningful throughput drift."],"primary_variable":"architecture","self_review":"This obeys the one-variable rule and avoids the previously policy-rejected asymmetric candidate. It is the most informative matched probe because it differs from the current mainline by exactly one structural element: the existence of the second residual stage. More distant probes like factorized_topk or lowrank_residual answer broader questions but are less diagnostic for the current mainline family.","summary":"Probe ARCHITECTURE=lowrank_soft_codebook_residual with the mainline K=128, EF=2, signum, LR=3.0e-3 recipe unchanged. This directly tests whether the extra second-stage residual refinement in the current mainline is worth its added online selection cost and runtime in the LUTurbo-compatible low-EF setting.","touched_files":[]}
research/history/logs/agent_action_0043.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"Round 42 answered the loss question cleanly: removing the auxiliary term produced an almost identical curve shape and a slightly worse endpoint than the `gated+signum+LR=2.0e-3` anchor, so the loss branch does not look promising. The next single question in the prescribed order is therefore preprocess: with the strengthened `gated` mainline recipe fixed at `K=128, EF=12, signum, LR=2.0e-3`, does enabling Hadamard preprocessing improve conditioning enough to lower the full training curve, or is the plain input path still best?","summary":"Stay on the active `gated` family and restore the current anchor recipe at `ARCHITECTURE=gated`, `K=128`, `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12`, `OPTIMIZER=signum`, `LR=2.0e-3`, and `AUXK_ALPHA=0.03125`, with the same runtime knobs pinned, and change only the preprocess variable by enabling `USE_HADAMARD=1`. Judge this round by the whole trajectory, not just terminal FVU: if Hadamard conditioning makes early and mid training smoother and finishes below the current `0.148156` anchor, keep preprocess live; if it is neutral or worse again, close the preprocess branch and then move on to K mapping.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"full","expected_win":"lower_fvu","family_name":"gated","family_stage":"mainline","self_review":"This stays on the same family, respects the fixed `EF=12` rule, and changes exactly one non-core variable after the optimizer and loss branches both failed to improve the updated anchor. I am not spending another round on loss because Round 42 reproduced the Round 39 curve almost exactly and only regressed at the endpoint, which is not enough evidence for a nearby aux sweep. The main risk is that Hadamard already failed at the older `LR=1.6e-3` anchor, but the stronger `2.0e-3` recipe may change the conditioning tradeoff, making this the cleanest remaining recipe question before touching K.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"gated"},{"key":"K","value":"128"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"12"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"2.0e-3"},{"key":"BATCH_SIZE","value":"1"},{"key":"GRAD_ACC_STEPS","value":"8"},{"key":"MICRO_ACC_STEPS","value":"1"},{"key":"AUXK_ALPHA","value":"0.03125"},{"key":"DEAD_FEATURE_THRESHOLD","value":"10000000"},{"key":"USE_HADAMARD","value":"1"},{"key":"COMPILE_MODEL","value":"1"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["Round 42 showed that `AUXK_ALPHA=0.0` is effectively neutral-to-worse relative to the `gated+signum+LR=2.0e-3` anchor: the curve was nearly identical and the endpoint regressed slightly, so the loss branch should not be expanded.","Round 43 isolates the remaining preprocess question on the updated `gated` anchor by enabling `USE_HADAMARD=1` at fixed `K=128, EF=12, signum, LR=2.0e-3`."],"next_hypotheses":["If `USE_HADAMARD=1` improves the full curve or endpoint, keep preprocess active with at most one nearby confirmation on the same anchor.","If Hadamard is neutral or worse again, close the recipe branch for this family and move on to K exploration to map where `gated` remains superior to `topk`."],"primary_variable":"preprocess"}
research/history/round_summaries/round_0232.json:7:  "family_name": "jumprelu",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0232.json:19:    "hypothesis": "\u5019\u9009 family: jumprelu\u3002\u6700\u7ec8\u91cd\u6784\u516c\u5f0f\u4e3a x_hat = \u03a3_i \u03b1_i b_i\uff0c\u5176\u4e2d {b_i} \u6765\u81ea\u5355\u4e2a\u9759\u6001\u5411\u91cf\u5e93\uff1bJumpReLU \u53ea\u6539\u53d8\u5355\u6837\u672c\u5728\u7ebf\u4fa7\u7684\u9608\u503c\u5316\u652f\u6301\u5f62\u6210\u4e0e\u7cfb\u6570\u8ba1\u7b97\uff0c\u4e0d\u6539\u53d8 decoder \u7aef\u7684\u5355\u5e93\u6709\u9650\u52a0\u6743\u548c\u5f62\u5f0f\uff0c\u56e0\u6b64\u53ef\u76f4\u63a5\u5bfc\u51fa\u5230 LUTurbo/Lottable \u7684\u201c\u67e5\u8868 + \u52a0\u6743\u6c42\u548c + \u9009\u62e9\u6027\u8865\u507f\u201d\u63a8\u7406\u94fe\u8def\uff0c\u517c\u5bb9\u6027\u5224\u65ad\u4e3a\u76f4\u63a5\u517c\u5bb9\u3002\u76f8\u5bf9 r227 \u53ea\u6539\u4e00\u4e2a env \u53c2\u6570 `JUMPRELU_INIT_THRESHOLD=0.05`\uff0c\u4fdd\u6301 `JUMPRELU_BANDWIDTH=0.05`\u3001`K=248`\u3001`EXPANSION_FACTOR=1`\u3001`signum`\u3001`LR=0.003` \u53ca\u5176\u4f59\u914d\u7f6e\u4e0d\u53d8\uff0c\u6d4b\u8bd5\u5728\u5f53\u524d\u6700\u5f3a `<0.5x` \u76f4\u517c\u5bb9\u70b9\u4e0a\uff0c\u66f4\u79ef\u6781\u7684\u6b63\u9608\u503c\u521d\u59cb\u5316\u662f\u5426\u80fd\u7ee7\u7eed\u6291\u5236\u9ad8 K \u4f4e EF regime \u4e0b\u7684\u5c0f\u566a\u58f0\u6fc0\u6d3b\uff0c\u628a FVU \u4ece r227 \u7684 0.14564 \u8fdb\u4e00\u6b65\u538b\u4f4e\uff0c\u540c\u65f6\u4e0d\u727a\u7272\u5176\u76f8\u5bf9 topk \u5df2\u7ecf\u8868\u73b0\u51fa\u7684\u7cfb\u7edf\u4fa7\u4f18\u52bf\u3002\u4e4b\u6240\u4ee5\u672c\u8f6e\u4e0d\u518d\u65b0\u5f00\u522b\u7684\u4f4e\u6210\u672c family\uff0c\u662f\u56e0\u4e3a\u5f53\u524d\u53ef\u884c\u5019\u9009\u91cc\uff1a`factorized_topk` \u5df2\u88ab r230 \u8bc1\u4f2a\u3001`group_topk` \u5df2\u88ab r231 \u8bc1\u4f2a\u3001`adaptive_budget_topk` \u5728 batch_size=1 \u4e0b\u9000\u5316\u4e3a\u666e\u901a topk\uff0c\u800c `gated/routed/whitened_topk/codebook_topk/two_stage_residual` \u5728 EF=1 \u4e0b\u5df2\u8d85\u51fa\u6210\u672c\u7ea6\u675f\uff1b\u56e0\u6b64\u5f53\u524d\u6700\u6709\u4ef7\u503c\u7684\u4f4e\u5f00\u9500\u52a8\u4f5c\uff0c\u662f\u5728\u5df2\u8bc1\u5b9e\u53ef\u6253\u5230 `<0.5x` \u524d\u6cbf\u7684 jumprelu \u5f3a\u70b9\u4e0a\u505a\u4e00\u6b21\u5355\u53d8\u91cf\u5f3a\u5316\uff0c\u800c\u4e0d\u662f\u5f00\u542f\u4e00\u4e2a\u5927\u6982\u7387\u4e0d\u6ee1\u8db3\u9884\u7b97\u6216\u4fe1\u606f\u589e\u76ca\u66f4\u4f4e\u7684\u65b0\u652f\u7ebf\u3002",
